user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following do_append code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 21.17.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17 is Use of the string handling functions from <string.h> shall not result in accesses beyond the bounds of the objects referenced by their pointer parameters.
This rule strictly applies to the Standard Library functions in <string.h> such as memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, and strspn.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of do_append.
```c
static enum MHD_Result
do_append (char **ret,
           const char *data,
           size_t size)
{
  char *buf;
  size_t old_len;

  if (NULL == *ret)
    old_len = 0;
  else
    old_len = strlen (*ret);
  if (NULL == (buf = malloc (old_len + size + 1)))
    return MHD_NO;
  if (NULL != *ret)
  {
    memcpy (buf,
            *ret,
            old_len);
    free (*ret);
  }
  memcpy (&buf[old_len],
          data,
          size);
  buf[old_len + size] = '\0';
  *ret = buf;
  return MHD_YES;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
Yes. The call memcpy(buf, *ret, old_len) can write/read out of bounds if the allocation size is incorrect. In particular, the code does not check for overflow when computing malloc(old_len + size + 1). If old_len + size + 1 wraps (size_t overflow), malloc may return a buffer smaller than old_len, and memcpy(buf, *ret, old_len) will write beyond the destination buffer. Example: old_len = 100 and size = SIZE_MAX - 50 yields old_len + size + 1 wrapping to 49; malloc(49) may succeed but copying old_len (100) bytes overruns buf. Also, if *ret were not a properly NUL-terminated string, strlen(*ret) itself could read beyond the source object leading to an invalid old_len and subsequent out-of-bounds memcpy.
</scenario>
